abstract = {This paper proposes an innovative multimodal emotion perception framework to improve the accuracy of financial volatility prediction by fusing social media graphic data. Traditional studies mainly rely on a single textual modality, which makes it difficult to capture the implicit emotions in visual information and the scarcity of labelled data in the financial domain. In this paper, we propose three core innovations: combining social media text (e.g., comments) and images (e.g., emoticons, news screenshots) to achieve adaptive fusion of graphical and textual features through a cross-modal attention mechanism to improve the completeness of emotion representation; adopting a two-stage strategy of pre-training and fine-tuning; and utilising a general multimodal dataset (MVSA) to pre-train the model, and using a two-stage strategy of pre-training to fine-tune the model. The two-stage strategy of ‘pre-training-fine-tuning’ is adopted to pre-train the model using the Universal Multimodal Data Set (MVSA), and then fine-tune it with the financial domain corpus to alleviate the problem of data scarcity; the multimodal sentiment factor is embedded into the classical HAR volatility model to construct the Sentiment-HAR model, and the leading effect of sentiment index on volatility is verified by the Granger causality test (γ=0.15,p=0.001). The experimental results show that the multimodal fusion model sentiment classification accuracy reaches 78\% (8.3\% improvement over the single-text model), and the sentiment index is significantly positively correlated with market volatility (Pearson r=0.32p&lt;0.01). The model robustly captures the dynamic correlation between sentiment and volatility during extreme events such as the COVID-19 epidemic and the Russia-Ukraine conflict. This study provides new theoretical and instrumental support for financial sentiment analysis and quantitative trading strategy design.},
