abstract = {Intent detection and slot filling are core sub-tasks in natural language understanding for building intelligent dialogue systems. This paper proposes a joint model named GAT-SAL, which integrates subword attention mechanisms and graph attention networks to address semantic loss caused by BERT's Wordpiece tokenization and to enhance bidirectional semantic interactions between intent and slot features. The model adopts a two-stage feature fusion strategy: in the first stage, the GAT module explicitly constructs a semantic graph between intent and slot features; in the second stage, the subword attention fusion layer enriches the semantic representation of complex words by aggregating subword-level information. Experimental results on two benchmark datasets, ATIS and SNIPS, demonstrate that GAT-SAL achieves state-of-the-art performance across multiple evaluation metrics, including intent classification accuracy, slot filling F1 score, and sentence-level semantic frame accuracy. Specifically, the model achieves 98.54\% intent accuracy, 97.22\% slot filling F1, and 89.70\% sentence-level accuracy on the ATIS dataset; and 98.72\%, 97.60\%, and 92.86\% respectively on the SNIPS dataset. In addition, ablation studies further confirm the importance of each module (SAL, GAT, and CRF) in contributing to the overall performance of the model.},
